1. Stack memory (C)

What it is

Memory used for function calls

Automatically managed (you don’t allocate/free it manually)

What lives on the stack

Local variables

Function parameters

Return addresses

void foo() {
    int x = 5;   // stack
}


Key properties

Fast

Automatically freed when the function returns

Limited size

Lifetime = scope of the function

Think of it as:

“Temporary working memory for functions”

2. The “other memory”: Heap

Heap memory

Dynamically allocated at runtime

Managed manually with malloc, calloc, realloc, free

int *p = malloc(sizeof(int)); // heap
*p = 5;
free(p);


Key properties

Slower than stack

Much larger

Lifetime = until you free it

Shared across functions

Think of it as:

“Long-lived memory you explicitly manage”

3. Static / Global memory (often forgotten)

This is neither stack nor heap.

What lives here

Global variables

static variables

String literals

static int counter = 0;  // static storage
int global = 10;         // global storage


Key properties

Exists for the entire program runtime

Allocated at program load time

4. ROM / Read-Only Memory (important for const char *)

In C, ROM is not a keyword, but a concept.

String literals
const char *s = "hello";


"hello" is stored in read-only memory (or read-only segment)

s (the pointer) is usually on the stack

The characters themselves are not writable

s[0] = 'H';  // ❌ undefined behavior (often segfault)


This memory is typically called:

RODATA

Read-only data segment

Backed by ROM/flash on embedded systems

Compare with writable array
char s[] = "hello";


The array is stored on the stack (if local)

Contents are copied from ROM

Writable

s[0] = 'H';  // ✅ OK

5. Quick summary table
Memory 	Type		Managed By		Lifetime		Writable	Example
===============================================================================================
Stack			CompilerFunction 	scope			Yes		int x;
Heap			Programmer		Until free()		Yes		malloc()
Static/Global		Program loader		Entire program		Yes		static int x;
ROM / RODATA		Program image		Entire program		❌ No		"hello"





calloc
void *calloc(size_t nmemb, size_t size);


What it does

Allocates memory for nmemb elements

Initializes all bytes to zero

int *a = calloc(10, sizeof(int));  // 10 ints, all = 0


Key points

Zero-initialized (0, NULL, '\0')

Slightly slower than malloc (because of clearing)

Good when you need clean/known initial state


How calloc really works
void *calloc(size_t nmemb, size_t size);


Internally, it does roughly this:

total_bytes = nmemb * size;
ptr = malloc(total_bytes);
memset(ptr, 0, total_bytes);


So:

nmemb → how many items

size → how big each item is (in bytes)

Concrete examples
Allocate 10 integers
int *a = calloc(10, sizeof(int));


nmemb = 10

size = 4 (typically)

Total bytes = 10 * 4 = 40

Allocate 256 bytes
void *buf = calloc(256, 1);


256 elements

each 1 byte

total = 256 bytes

Allocate a struct array
struct node *nodes = calloc(100, sizeof(struct node));


100 nodes

each node = sizeof(struct node) bytes

Why not just pass bytes?

Because calloc:

Understands arrays

Can check for overflow in nmemb * size

Makes intent clearer: “allocate N things”

This is safer than:

malloc(nmemb * size); // overflow risk if not careful

Key pitfall to remember

❌ Wrong:

calloc(sizeof(int), 10);   // swapped — allocates wrong amount


✅ Right:

calloc(10, sizeof(int));

One-liner mental model

calloc(n, size) = allocate space for n objects of size bytes each, all set to zero






realloc
void *realloc(void *ptr, size_t new_size);


What it does

Resizes an existing heap allocation

May move the block to a new location

Preserves existing data (up to min(old, new))

int *a = malloc(5 * sizeof(int));
a = realloc(a, 10 * sizeof(int));  // grow


Important rules

If it moves, the old pointer becomes invalid

If it fails, returns NULL and original block is unchanged

New memory (if grown) is uninitialized

Safe pattern

int *tmp = realloc(a, 10 * sizeof(int));
if (tmp) {
    a = tmp;
}

Special realloc cases
realloc(NULL, size)   // same as malloc(size)
realloc(ptr, 0)       // frees ptr (implementation-defined return)

Quick comparison
Function	Allocates    Resizes	  Zeroes memory
malloc		✅	     ❌		  ❌
calloc		✅	     ❌		  ✅
realloc		❌	     ✅		  ❌
One-sentence memory model

calloc = allocate + zero
realloc = resize while keeping old data




MEMORY LEAK:

Definition (C-centric)

A memory leak in C is when dynamically allocated memory becomes unreachable (you lose the pointer to it) before it is freed.

Important correction to your statement ❌

“Is it when allocated memory is not freed after a program has finished running?”

Not quite.

When a program exits, the OS reclaims all memory anyway

That alone is not what defines a memory leak in C

What actually makes it a leak
Classic leak
void f(void) {
    int *p = malloc(sizeof(int));
    p = NULL;   // leak: original pointer lost
}


Memory is still allocated

Program can never free it

Leak occurs while the program is running

Another leak example
int *p = malloc(100);
p = realloc(p, 200);
if (!p) {
    // original pointer lost → leak
}

What is NOT a memory leak
Memory freed correctly
int *p = malloc(100);
free(p);

Program exits without freeing (OS cleanup)
int *p = malloc(100);
// program ends


Bad style

But not a leak in the strict sense

Leak detectors may still warn, but OS reclaims memory

One-sentence rule to remember

A memory leak happens when allocated memory is still allocated but no longer reachable by the program.
